article.description: Bill Laimbeer was tossed from the Detroit Shock's 69-48 win over the Miami Sol on Saturday night with a 22-point lead and four mninutes to go -- a little unusual for a coach, even when he's a former "Bad Boy."
article.headline: Laimbeer says he released pent up emotions
article.linkText: Laimbeer gets tossed even as his Shock rip Sol
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- Getting thrown out of a basketball game is nothing new to Bill Laimbeer. But getting tossed from the Detroit Shock's 69-48 win over the Miami Sol on Saturday night with a 22-point lead and four mninutes to go is a little unusual -- even for a member the Detroit Pistons "Bad Boys'' championship teams of the late 1980s. "When you are 4-17, you are going to have frustrations, and I let them out tonight,'' Shock coach Laimbeer said. "I was just smart enough to wait until we got up by 20.'' Swin Cash scored 11 points and Astou Ndiaye-Diatta added 10 for the Shock, who won their fourth straight at home by their largest margin of victory this season. "I'm really impressed with how hard this team plays,'' said Elaine Powell, who joined the Shock in a trade with Orlando on July 7. "We don't have a great record, but we play hard for 40 minutes every night.'' Miami (10-12) had its three-game road winning streak snapped as it matched its worst loss of the year. "They beat us inside, they beat us outside and they beat us every which way,'' Sol coach Ron Rothstein said. "They were good and we were terrible.'' Cash and Ndiaye-Diatta were the only players to reach double figures. Powell and Deanna Nolan had nine each for Detroit. Claudia Neves led Miami with nine points. The Shock jumped out to a 15-3 lead as the Sol missed 14 of their first 15 shots. Powell banked in an offbalance 3-pointer at the buzzer to give Detroit a 36-19 lead at halftime. "That was probably 50 percent our defense and 50 percent their shooting,'' Laimbeer said. "We have been able to take the inside away from teams and make them shoot jumpers. That has helped us a lot. We have some limitations, but we've also got a lot of talent.'' Detroit put the game away with a 11-2 run to start the second half, giving the Shock a 47-21 lead with 14 minutes to play. They led by as many as 26 down the stretch. "They executed well and we just got beat all over the floor,'' Miami guard Debbie Black said.

Game notes
Tayshaun Prince, the Detroit Pistons' first-round draft pick, attended the game. ... Shock players Edwina Brown and Dominque Canty lost most of their belongings when their apartment building burned down Friday night. The Shock canceled the morning shoot-around so that teammates could help them get situated in new lodgings. ... Sol coach Ron Rothstein was Laimbeer's coach in 1992-93 with the Pistons. ... Laimbeer's ejection was the first for a Shock coach in team history.
